    <slides:slide>
        <h1>MAC Address</h1>
        <ul>
            <li>6- or 8-Byte MAC Address</li>
            <li>MAC: Media Access Control</li>
            <li>EUI: Extended Unique Identifier</li>
            <li>Other names: Ethernet Address, Hardware Address, Physical Address</li>
            <li>
                Standards:
                <ul>
                    <li>MAC-48</li>
                    <li>EUI-48</li>
                    <li>EUI-64</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                MAC-48 / EUI-48 used in:
                <ul>
                    <li>Ethernet</li>
                    <li>IEEE 802.11 wireless networks</li>
                    <li>Bluetooth</li>
                    <li>IEEE 802.5 token ring</li>
                    <li>Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI)</li>
                    <li>Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) as part of its NSAP address</li>
                    <li>Fibre Channel</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                EUI-64 is used in:
                <ul>
                    <li>FireWire</li>
                    <li>IPv6</li>
                    <li>ZigBee / 802.15.4 / 6LoWPAN</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                Common Notations:
                <ul>
                    <li><code>01:23:45:67:89:ab</code></li>
                    <li><code>01-23-45-67-89-ab</code></li>
                    <li><code>0123.4567.89ab</code></li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </slides:slide>
    <slides:slide>
        <h1>POP3</h1>
        <ul>
            <li>Post Office Protocol Version 3</li>
            <li>Used for remote access to E-Mail</li>
            <li>Mail must be downloaded before reading</li>
            <li>Very simple, no folders</li>
        </ul>
    </slides:slide>
    <slides:slide>
        <h1>IMAP4</h1>
        <ul>
            <li>Internet Mail Access Protocol Version 4</li>
            <li>Used for remote access to E-Mail</li>
            <li>Mail can be read "online"</li>
            <li>Folders possible</li>
        </ul>
    </slides:slide>
